ny, Eure, Normandy, France":"Corny, Eure, Normandie, Frankrijk","Conches, Seine-Et-Marne, Île-De-France, France":"Conches, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, Frankrijk","Saint Pierre-Du-Bosguérard, Eure, Haute-Normandie, France":"Saint-Pierre-du-Bosguérard, Eure, Haute-Normandie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"9 September 990–31 May 1039":"9 September 0990–31 May 1039","1004–1075":"1004–1075","1035–1070":"1035–1070","0990–1039":"0990–1039","June 1039":"June 1039","1039":"1039","1004":"1004","31 May 1039":"31 May 1039","9 September 990":"9 September 0990","1035":"1035","0990":"0990","1075":"1075","1070":"1070","Guerny, Eure, Upper Normandy, France":"Guerny, Eure, Normandy, France","Tosny, Eure, Normandy, France":"Corny, Eure, Normandy, France","Conches, Seine-Et-Marne, Île-De-France, France":"Conches, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, France","Saint Pierre-Du-Bosguérard, Eure, Haute-Normandie, France":"Saint-Pierre-du-Bosguérard, Eure, Upper Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Toeni","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Alberto, Aldo, Alessandro, Anselmo, Beto, Eugenio, Italo, Luigi, Sergio, Silva.","Italian: from a short form of the personal name <i>Antonio</i> (see   Anthony  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Anthony","meanings":["English and West Indian (mainly Antigua and Barbuda, Saint Lucia, and Trinidad and Tobago, also Dutch Caribbean): from the personal name <i>Anthony</i>, Latin <i>Antonius</i>, which, with its variants and cognates, is one of the commonest personal names in Europe. Spellings with <i>-h-</i>, which first appear in English in the 16th century and in French (as <i>Anthoine</i>) at about the same time, are due to the erroneous belief that the name derives from Greek <i>anthos</i> ‘flower’. The popularity of the personal name in Christendom is largely due to the cult of the Egyptian hermit Saint Anthony (  AD  251–356), who in his old age gathered a community of hermits around him, and for that reason is regarded by some as the founder of monasticism. It was further increased by the fame of Saint Anthony of Padua (1195–1231), who long enjoyed a great popular cult and who is believed to help people find lost things. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates and derivatives (patronymics) from other languages, for example Greek patronymic   Antoniades  , Italian   Antoni  , Polish   Antoniewicz  , Croatian and Serbian <b>Antonović</b> (see   Antonovich  ) and <b>Antunović</b>; see also below. The name <i>Anthony</i> is also found among Christians in southern India, but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US. Compare   Antony  .","German, Flemish, and French (mainly Alsace): Latinized (humanistic) patronymic from local equivalents of the Latin personal name <i>Antonius</i>, from its genitive form <i>Antoni(i)</i>. In North America, this surname is also an altered form of the German, Dutch, French, and Slovak cognates   Antoni   1 and   Antony   2.","History: John Anthony of Hampstead, Middlesex, England (now part of north London) migrated to Boston, MA, in 1634. By 1640 he had moved to Providence, RI, where his descendants are still established."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lord Ralph De Toeni Of Conches was born on 9 September 0990, in Guerny, Eure, Normandy, France. He had at least 1 daughter with Alice Godehilde Fitzwilliam. He died on 31 May 1039, in Conches, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, France, at the age of 48, and was buried in Saint-Pierre-du-Bosguérard, Eure, Upper Normandy, France."},"et":{"9 September 990–31 May 1039":"9. september 0990–31. mai 1039","1004–1075":"1004–1075","1035–1070":"1035–1070","0990–1039":"0990–1039","June 1039":"juuni 1039","1039":"1039","1004":"1004","31 May 1039":"31. mai 1039","9 September 990":"9. september 0990","1035":"1035","0990":"0990","1075":"1075","1070":"1070","Guerny, Eure, Upper Normandy, France":"Guerny, Eure, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Tosny, Eure, Normandy, France":"Corny, Eure, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Conches, Seine-Et-Marne, Île-De-France, France":"Conches, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Saint Pierre-Du-Bosguérard, Eure, Haute-Normandie, France":"Saint-Pierre-du-Bosguérard, Eure, Haute-Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"9 September 990–31 May 1039":"9. syyskuuta 0990–31. toukokuuta 1039","1004–1075":"1004–1075","1035–1070":"1035–1070","0990–1039":"0990–1039","June 1039":"kesäkuu 1039","1039":"1039","1004":"1004","31 May 1039":"31.